
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `dpkg-query` baraye gereftan etela'at dar morede package-haye `deb` (Debian package) nasb shode dar system estefade mishavad.  Mitavan az aan baraye fahmidane versiyon, tarikh nasb, va digar etela'at package-ha estefade kard.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `dpkg-query -l [esm-e-package]` --> 📜 List kardan etela'at dar morede yek ya chand package. Agar esm-e-package dade nashavad, hameye package-haye nasb shode ra neshon midahad.
    🔹 `dpkg-query -s [esm-e-package]` --> 👀 Namayesh etela'ate kamel (status) yek package.
    🔹 `dpkg-query -L [esm-e-package]` --> 📁 List kardan hameye file-haei ke yek package nasb karde ast.
    🔹 `dpkg-query -W [esm-e-package]` --> 🔍 Namayesh name va versiyon package dar yek khatt.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ dpkg-query -l firefox

    🔹 Namayesh etela'at dar morede package `firefox`.

    $ dpkg-query -s apache2

    🔹 Namayesh etela'ate kamel dar morede package `apache2`.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ dpkg-query -l | grep nano

    🔹 Peida kardan va namayesh package-haye nasb shode ke esm-e `nano` dar aanha vojood darad.  In komak mikonad package-haye marboote be `nano` ra peida konid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `dpkg-query` command is used to retrieve information about installed `deb` (Debian package) packages on your system. You can use it to find out the version, installation date, and other details of packages.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `dpkg-query -l [package-name]` --> 📜 List information about one or more packages. If no package name is provided, it will show all installed packages.
    🔹 `dpkg-query -s [package-name]` --> 👀 Display full status information of a package.
    🔹 `dpkg-query -L [package-name]` --> 📁 List all files that a package installed.
    🔹 `dpkg-query -W [package-name]` --> 🔍 Display package name and version in one line.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ dpkg-query -l firefox

    🔹 Show information about the `firefox` package.

    $ dpkg-query -s apache2

    🔹 Show detailed information about the `apache2` package.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ dpkg-query -l | grep nano

    🔹 Find and display installed packages that have `nano` in their name. This helps to find packages related to `nano`.
